04787nam a22007215i 9781501723605DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182001nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017236057 a10.7591/97815017236052doi  a(DE-B1597)514759  a(OCoLC)1083621504  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a340/.12231 aCrotty, Kevin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLaw's Interior :bLegal and Literary Constructions of the Self /cKevin Crotty. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. The Quest for Autonomy: Modern Jurisprudence and the Oresteia -- t1. AUTONOMY AS AN ASPIRATION -- t2. THE Oresteia AND THE DRAMA OF AUTONOMY -- t3. LAW AND THE POLITICS OF RECOGNITION -- t4. ON LAW AND LITERATURE -- tCHAPTER 2. Dilemmas of the Self: Law and Confession -- t1. CONFESSION IN LAW AND THEORY -- t2. AUGUSTINE AND THE CONFESSING SELF -- t3. THE LIMITED STATE AND THE INTRICATE SELF -- t4. LAW AS PRACTICE -- tCHAPTER 3. Rationality and Imagination in the Law: Jürgen Habermas and Wallace Stevens -- t1. THE RATIONALITY OF LAW -- t2. STEVENS ON EVIL -- t3. ON RIGHTS AND THE INDIVIDUAL -- t4. LAW AS AN “IMAGINATION OF THE NORMAL” -- tConclusion: Law’s Interior -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Law's Interior, Kevin M. Crotty draws on several important literary works to offer a new model of the relationship between citizens and their laws, one that emphasizes the power of law to shape citizens and to foster—or discourage—their autonomy. Crotty maintains that citizens are "inside" the law—they are the law's interior. Literature, he finds, can be relevant to law by emphasizing the connections between law and the world around it—a stance that corrects the tendency of legal theory to treat law as a separate, autonomous entity.The texts Crotty examines—Aeschylus' Oresteia, St. Augustine's Confessions, and the poetry of Wallace Stevens—question the rationalist optimism that Crotty regards as distorting much recent theorizing about law. Further, he asserts that the inability of courts to state clearly the principles animating their decisions demonstrates the stranglehold the positivist model has on us and our legal imaginations.Crotty sketches a model of the relation between citizens and laws that supplements the more familiar idea of law as something deliberated and enacted by rational, inherently autonomous citizens. The most important legal decisions of the past fifty years, Crotty says, rest on the perception that the state, far from merely respecting the "innate" autonomy of its citizens, actively shapes that autonomy. Law's Interior should contribute to a better understanding of the real principles underlying some landmark decisions by the Supreme Court.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAutonomy (Psychology). 0aIndividualismxSocial aspects. 0aLawxPhilosophy. 0aLiberty. 0aPersonality (Law). 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPoetry & Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172360540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501723605423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501723605/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGru